message.content:
1. Go to the homepage of the blog on Blogger.

2. Look for a section called "About Me" or something similar, usually located in the sidebar or footer of the page. This is where the blogger typically writes a short bio and may include their name.

3. Check at the end of individual blog posts, where many bloggers sign off with their name.

4. Use social media icons on the blog if they are available since many people link to their personal profiles from their blogs – they might have provided a link to Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, etc., which could display their real name.
 
5. Many times there is an “author” listed for each post which displays when opening one article– you can check there to see if it says who wrote it (i.e., Blog/Article: XYZ - by John Doe). 

6.Try using Google’s “site:” search feature by typing in "[blog_URL] About Us" without quotations into Google search engine and replace [blog_URL] with either URL/domain/address/name/etc including extensions like .com/.net/etc just as long whichever information describing said web address (but excluding any www).

7.Perform some cross-reference searches using details found on site mixed up within other platforms online whether professional networks/services based out connecting users/people/accounts/profiles sharing same title/company+role/team/city/country/name/school/current/former intern(ex), e.g LinkedIn your related cases/content authors/research/self-publishing website/database/subscribers/bloggers/witnesses/passions background/info field/intern area/lifestyles industries/experience reputation/ratings/state/site's domain/full description/license/exp/Patents/names around production process/spaces filled ID documents/original format/issues/subject-of line(for ex
